g or traumatic histories. Koshar argues that in Germany, memory landscapes have taken shape according to four separate paradigms--the national monument, the ruin, the reconstruction, and the trace--which he analyzes in relation to the changing political agendas that have guided them over time. Despite the massive ruptures of Germany's history, we see that significant continuities have served to counterbalance the traumas of the German past.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aNational monumentszGermany. 0aNational socialismxMoral and ethical aspects. 0aPolitical culturezGermany. 0aSymbolism in politicszGermany. 0aWar and civilization. 0aWar memorialszGermany. 4aEurope. 4aGeneral. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aKoshar, Rudy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052021768340uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052092252540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922525423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520922525/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles